# .dockerignore — what NOT to send to the Docker build context.
#
# This is the image-based analogue of Lab 04's .deployignore. The build context
# is everything Docker tars up and hands to the daemon before running the
# Dockerfile. Anything matched here:
#   - never enters the build context (faster builds, smaller upload)
#   - can never be COPY-ed into the image by accident (smaller, cleaner image)
#   - keeps secrets and lab tooling out of a published artifact
#
# Format: same glob rules as .gitignore. One pattern per line.
#
# Rule of thumb: the only things the Dockerfile actually COPYs are projects/,
# services/config/, services/modules.json, and third-party-modules/. Everything
# else is noise in the build context — exclude it.

# Version control + git internals
.git/
.gitignore
.gitattributes

# Secrets and local env (NEVER bake these into a published image)
.env
.env.example

# Lab teaching material — has nothing to do with the gateway runtime
README.md
LICENSE
docs/
exercises/
instructor-notes/
scripts/
tests/

# CI / compose / dev-only files
.github/
docker-compose.yaml
Dockerfile
.dockerignore

# Database bootstrap (runs in the TimescaleDB sidecar, not the gateway image)
db-init/

# Per-instance keystores and secrets. The actual keystore files are gitignored
# (regenerated per gateway), so they're never in the build context — these
# patterns are belt-and-suspenders so a stray keystore can't get baked into a
# shared image.
**/keystore/*.jks
**/keystore/*.p12
**/*.idb

# Ignition operational state + content-addressed blob noise — never bake these
**/.resources/
**/migration-log-*.md
**/data/db/
**/data/users.idb
**/data/temp/
**/data/logs/
**/data/.metadata/

# OS / editor noise
.DS_Store
Thumbs.db
.vscode/
.idea/
*.swp
